ction debts? What can the biodiversity hypothesis tell us about rapidly increasing allergies, asthma, and other chronic inflammatory disorders? The world’s largest island, Greenland, for instance, is the starting point for a journey into the benefits that humankind acquires from biodiversity, including the staggering biodiversity of microbes in the ecosystems that are closest to us—the ecosystems in our guts, in our respiratory tracts, and under our skin. Conceptually oriented but grounded in an adventurous personal narrative, Messages from Islands is a landmark work that lifts the natural mysteries of islands from the sea, bringing to light the thrilling complexities and connections of ecosystems worldwide.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aBiodiversity. 0aIsland ecology. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aecology, evolution, baltic sea, large tropical islands, borneo, madagascar, fieldwork, island biodiversity, biology, natural sciences, species, wildlife, fragmented landscapes, field studies, ecological questions, environment, conservation, environmentalism, environmental issues, extinction thresholds, allergies, asthma, chronic inflammatory disorders, greenland, ecosystems, respiratory tracts, personal narrative, habitat loss.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107109840 cprintz978022640630540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226406589423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226406589/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles